AB  - Solar-ice slurry systems may be a direct alternative to other thermal systems (such as, geothermal heat pumps), but the relation between the boundary conditions and its overall energetic performance is still somewhat unclear. The main purpose of this analysis is to study the energetic performance of two solar-ice slurry systems (one using carbon dioxide as refrigerant for the electrically driven heat pump and the other using propane) under a wide variety of boundary conditions, and to numerically calculate the impact of the main parameters in the overall performance of the system. In this regard, a parametric study has been carried out. The pytrnsys open-source simulation environment, based on TRNSYS, has been used to analyse the Seasonal Performance Factor (SPF) of solar-ice slurry systems in 14 different European locations, two different multifamily residential buildings (a new one and a refurbished one), four collector aperture areas and three ice storage volumes. Collector aperture area and ice storage volume have been sized respect to the total thermal demand of the building: the sum of Domestic Hot Water (DHW) and Space Heating (SH) demands. Numerical results show that the [Formula presented]-based system outperforms the propane-based one for new buildings, while the opposite happens for old ones. Also, it has been proved that an SPF up to 4 is possible in most central Europe climates using solar-ice slurry systems: a mean SPF value of 3.95 has been obtained in Brussels for the propane-based system and 3.70 in Strasbourg for the [Formula presented]-based system. For more extreme climates (like Warsaw or Helsinki), mean SPF values are reduced to 2.50 and 2.70 respectively. Furthermore, a regression model has been developed to calculate the SPF values of solar-ice slurry systems targeting multifamily residential buildings. The obtained expression has a Root Mean Square Error (RMSE) of 0.215 for the [Formula presented]-based system and 0.201 for the propane-based one. These expressions could be used to make an approximation of the energetic performance of both systems. It has been numerically proved that the most important parameter when it comes to the performance of a solar-ice slurry system is the solar irradiation on the collector area and more specifically, the winter solar irradiation. © 2024 The Authors
