AB  - Today, and into the future, technology will need to minimize environmental impacts while providing adequate energy with cost savings. Oil well conversion for geothermal direct use may meet these needs for rural communities. The Williston Basin has the necessary geological setting and production infrastructure, though often lacking localized techno-economic analysis of system potentials. This project provides such analysis. With an emphasis on alleviating energy poverty, providing jobs for the energy transition, and increasing local availability of nutritious food stock, a case study for Mandaree, North Dakota is made. Mandaree is a town in the West Segment of the MHA Nation on Fort Berthold Indian Reservation. There are more than 70 oil and gas wellheads within 3.5km of the town center, most exploiting Bakken shales at a depth greater than 3000m. At shallower depths are several hot sedimentary aquifers, with temperatures higher than required for modern district heating (<70C). Initial community survey indicates a desire for commercial greenhouses, both for jobs and nutritious food stocks. To meet these needs, as well as the domestic hot water and space heating demands of Mandaree, the focus is further narrowed to the Inyan Kara formation. The Inyan Kara formation is approximately 1550m below the surface with all abandoned wells penetrating the layer on their way to deeper drilling targets. From previous injection well and wastewater disposal studies, the formation has a high permeability and a thermostratigraphy derived temperature of greater than 80°. Analytical methods for open hole flow rates indicate potentials between 91-244 L/s of fluid production per well. This project isolates two abandoned, but not plugged, gas wells for a production-injection doublet configuration about 1400m from the town center. It explores the economic potential, technical considerations, and future work necessary to achieve some of the energetically enabled desires of the community. Copyright © 2021 Geothermal Rising.
