AB  - Due to its remoteness, extreme weather conditions, limited local energy availability, low population, and limited energy-transportation infrastructure, the region of Nunavik, located in the northernmost part of Québec (Canada), is fully dependent on imported refined petroleum products. They rely mainly on fuel oil for their heating needs, leading to high energy costs and sustainability issues. Recently, several studies were carried out to improve the energy independence and security of remote regions of Canada using renewable energies. However, on several occasions, energy sources and technologies were evaluated under different models and methodologies, which makes it difficult to identify the optimal combination of technical, economic and environmental alternatives. In this project, building energy simulations were conducted using SIMEB software in order to estimate the heating needs of a residential building located in the northern remote community of Umiujaq, Canada. The simulations were developed considering a 252 m2 one-floor house with 5 occupants. Several heating alternatives were studied to meet the heating needs of the building and to reduce the dependence on fossil fuels, the amount of greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions, and overall heating cost. These alternatives include wood pellet boilers, solar photovoltaics (PV) and geothermal heat pumps which were compared to conventional oil furnaces. An economic analysis was carried out through the development of a life cycle cost (LCC) analysis of each alternative considering environmental, technical, and economic issues. Simulation results give a residential building heating intensity of 324.39 kWh/m2 (space heating + domestic hot water). The LCC analysis shows that a mix of heating systems like geothermal heat pumps, biomass and solar PV represents an interesting alternative for Northern Québec with a levelized cost of energy (LCOE) that varies from 0.17 to 0.50 $/kWh, depending on the mix of technologies and their contribution to the heating needs. Conventional heating system based on fuel oil have a comparable cost of 0.21 $/kWh. Results could eventually be extended to similar subarctic settings in Canada and worldwide. © 2022 Geothermal Resources Council. All rights reserved.
