AB  - Plus-energy houses have until now been frontrunners: they are very often detached houscs or buildings in sparsely populated areas. But due to the on-going urban sprawl new solutions must be developed. The focus should be on the development of innovative multifunctional neighhourhoods using energetic synergies of building clusters. The key objective of the '+ERS - Plus Energy Network Reininghaus South" is the development of a comprehensive energy concept in the context of urban, thermal and building engineering for an entire city district. A combination of energy efficiency measures, energy production on site and energy exchange between the buildings will establish a plus energy housing estate. The project comprises an approximately I 7,000 sqm area providing work and living space for 500 people. Due to the different load and user profiles exchange of surplus energy between this two building complexes is possible. In winter energy supply for domestic hot water and space heating for the twelve residential buildings is provided by a geothermal system with ground tubes and heat pumps. In summer the ground tubes are used as a heat sink for the office and shop buildings. This paper highlights the main technical measures and strategies, the results of a Life Cycle Analysis (LCA), the results of the dynamic simulation of the Plus Energy Network, and also discusses the problems and hurdles of implementation.
