AB  - The energy sector in Slovakia (Central Europe) depends significantly on the import of natural gas and other primary energy sources from abroad. This dependence can only be reduced by decreasing the energy consumption and by utilizing renewable energy sources. Geothermal energy is one of the most perspective renewable energy sources in Slovakia due to the favourable hydrogeological conditions. To exploit this energy, two geothermal boreholes were drilled in the city of Galanta in 1983 and 1984. The boreholes were selected to supply energy to the energy central, from which the heat for Galanta - North housing estate is provided. There are 1,236 apartments in the housing estate, for which it is necessary to cover the heating and domestic hot water demand. In addition to the apartments, heat supply is provided for a hospital, a retirement home and a primary school. The open geothermal energy system with indirect use of geothermal energy, constructed in Galanta, presents an energy supply solution that is unique for the region of Central Europe. Geothermal energy presents the dominant heat source and covers 89 % to 97 % of the energy demand, supplemented by a peak backup heat generator fuelled by natural gas. The low temperature excessive geothermal water that remains in the end of the process is used for heat pumps and for filling the recreational pools. Thereby, maximum utilization of renewable energy is achieved. The paper presents practical experience with design and operation of this unique system.
